From: Claude (devcontainer agent)
Date: 2026-04-27
Subject: [S7+S8+S9+S10] Followup adjustments to post_install-correctness

Why this is a separate patch
============================
This devcontainer mounts /workspace/.devcontainer as read-only inside
the container, so an agent running inside cannot edit Dockerfile or
post_install.py directly. Apply this patch from the host (or any
environment with write access to .devcontainer/), then commit and push.

Order of application: this patch operates on the post_install.py STATE
that results from applying `2026-04-27-post_install-correctness-and-
hardening.patch` first (it modifies code introduced by that patch).
Apply order:

  1. paad/code-reviews/deferred/2026-04-27-post_install-correctness-and-hardening.patch
  2. paad/code-reviews/deferred/2026-04-27-fix_directory_ownership-symlink-args-walk.patch
  3. paad/code-reviews/deferred/2026-04-27-post_install-correctness-followup.patch  (this one)

What this fixes (review items S7, S8, S9, S10 ã review 2026-04-27 18:27)
========================================================================

S7 (Suggestion): _load_json_or_backup doesn't catch UnicodeDecodeError
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The parent patch's `_load_json_or_backup` catches `json.JSONDecodeError`
(a `ValueError` subclass) and `OSError` separately. But
`path.read_text()` runs BEFORE `json.loads(...)`, and on a
binary-content file (e.g. a corrupted `~/.claude.json` after some
prior failure) it raises `UnicodeDecodeError` ã which is a `ValueError`
subclass, NOT under `OSError`. The exception propagates out of
_load_json_or_backup unhandled and aborts postCreate.

Fix: broaden the first except to `(json.JSONDecodeError, UnicodeDecodeError)`.
Both produce the same recovery action (back up the bad file, start
fresh), so a tuple-except keeps the message and backup logic
unchanged.

S8 (Suggestion): _git_quote_value doesn't reject control characters
-------------------------------------------------------------------
`_git_quote_value` wraps a value in double quotes and escapes `\\` and
`"` ã but a host gitconfig with embedded `\\n`/`\\t`/`\\r` in a value
(rare, but a malicious-host vector or pre-existing corruption) would
round-trip through this function unchanged. Git's INI parser treats
`\\n` as a value-terminator (the next line starts a new key), so a
control-char value would silently corrupt `.gitconfig.local` ã
either misattributing later keys to the value or terminating the
identity section early.

Fix: refuse outright via `raise ValueError`. The exception is caught
by the surrounding try/except in setup_global_gitignore which warns
and continues; no clean round-trip exists for control chars in INI
format, so refusing is the only correct option.

S9 (Suggestion): [include] path bypasses _git_quote_value
---------------------------------------------------------
The parent patch's `use_full_include` branch emits `[include]\\n
    path = {host_gitconfig}\\n` raw ã NOT routed through
_git_quote_value. Latent today (host_gitconfig is `Path.home() /
".gitconfig"`, a fixed literal that can't contain INI metacharacters
on a sane host), but the moment a future env var lets users override
the include source, an unquoted path with `#`/`;`/leading whitespace
would silently corrupt the `[include]` section.

Fix: route the path through _git_quote_value too. Asymmetric defense
becomes symmetric defense.

S10 (Suggestion): commit.gpgsign quoting is gratuitous
------------------------------------------------------
`_git_quote_value(commit_gpgsign)` wraps a canonicalized boolean
(`true`/`false`/`yes`/`no`/`1`/`0`/`on`/`off` per git-config(1)) in
`"..."`. The boolean has no metacharacters that need quoting, and
wrapping risks future git parser tightening rejecting quoted booleans
(git already special-cases boolean parsing).

Fix: emit `commit_gpgsign` raw for this one key. The other identity
keys (user.name/user.email/user.signingkey) STAY quoted because they
DO carry user-supplied values that may contain metacharacters.

How to apply
============
From a shell on the host (NOT inside the devcontainer):

  cd <smudge repo root>
  # Apply the parent + I7/S5/S6 patches first (see Order of application)
  git apply paad/code-reviews/deferred/2026-04-27-post_install-correctness-followup.patch
  git add .devcontainer/post_install.py
  git commit -m "fix(devcontainer): post_install correctness followups (S7+S8+S9+S10)"

Then push.

